00:00:20.890 --> 00:00:24.240
PROFESSOR: Last time, under the
tutelage of Professor Blendi,

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:27.700
you started to see some
of the consequences,

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:31.780
the more immediate consequences,
of some of the properties

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:34.340
we've been discussing
over the last few lectures

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:36.760
of binary liquid mixtures.

00:00:36.760 --> 00:00:39.172
And in particular he
started showing you

00:00:39.172 --> 00:00:41.130
some of the colligative
properties by which you

00:00:41.130 --> 00:00:44.250
see changes in the vapor
pressure and the boiling point

00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:47.870
and so forth, that arise because
you've got liquids in mixtures

00:00:47.870 --> 00:00:50.140
and this affects their
chemical potentials.

00:00:50.140 --> 00:00:52.230
And today I want
to start by going

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:56.460
through the fourth colligative
property that's commonly seen,

00:00:56.460 --> 00:00:57.694
what called osmotic pressure.

00:00:57.694 --> 00:00:58.860
And I mentioned this before.

00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:01.210
Today we'll go through a
quantitative calculation

00:01:01.210 --> 00:01:02.350
of its effects.

00:01:02.350 --> 00:01:06.090
And then we'll start in on a
different unit of the course.

00:01:06.090 --> 00:01:07.930
We'll start in on
statistical mechanics.

00:01:07.930 --> 00:01:28.370
So let's continue with the
colligative properties.

00:01:28.370 --> 00:01:31.400
And osmotic pressure plays a
super-important role, certainly

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:35.100
in all of biology, because of
course inside biological cells

00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:36.419
you have solutions.

00:01:36.419 --> 00:01:38.210
Water is in there,
along with a whole bunch

00:01:38.210 --> 00:01:39.830
of other components.

00:01:39.830 --> 00:01:41.890
And so the chemical
potential of the water

00:01:41.890 --> 00:01:44.240
is strongly affected by
all the other constituents.

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:47.660
And this has profound
effects on what's

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:50.620
involved in maintaining an
equilibrium between what

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:53.040
goes on inside and
outside of the cell.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:54.850
And this is the case
in all organisms.

00:01:54.850 --> 00:01:56.410
And it's also
exploited of course

00:01:56.410 --> 00:01:59.350
in all sorts of other contexts.

00:01:59.350 --> 00:02:04.280
So what's happening with
osmotic pressure is,

00:02:04.280 --> 00:02:09.280
you've got some
situation where there's

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:11.880
a semi-permeable membrane.

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:13.690
It allows one of
the constituents

00:02:13.690 --> 00:02:15.460
but not others to pass through.

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:16.590
And typically that's water.

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:18.550
Although, of course,
it could be anything.

00:02:18.550 --> 00:02:24.090
So, in the lab the way
this typically looks

00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:30.370
is something like this.

00:02:30.370 --> 00:02:42.080
Here's your
semi-permeable membrane.

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:45.940
Outside, we can
imagine that there's

00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:49.580
pure liquid A. Could be water,
could be something else.

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:54.430
Inside, you've got
A mixed with B,

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:59.180
one or more other constituents.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:04.000
And then there's some
level of the liquid

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:05.480
outside the container.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:10.350
Of course, A can pass between,
pass through, the membrane.

00:03:10.350 --> 00:03:13.340
And so what ends up
happening is, if you just

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:15.470
look at the situation,
what you immediately

00:03:15.470 --> 00:03:19.580
notice is that
the liquid in here

00:03:19.580 --> 00:03:27.852
goes up higher than
the liquid around it.

00:03:27.852 --> 00:03:28.810
It's at a higher level.

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:30.270
It seems counterintuitive
at first.

00:03:30.270 --> 00:03:32.880
And in fact it can
be enormously higher.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:35.030
But that's what happens.

00:03:35.030 --> 00:03:47.690
So there's extra height, h,
of liquid inside the container

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:50.910
relative to what's outside it.

00:03:50.910 --> 00:03:52.970
And what that means is
the pressure inside here

00:03:52.970 --> 00:03:54.100
must be higher, right?

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:56.160
Of course, the
weight of this liquid

00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:59.730
is pushing down on
what's down here.

00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:02.210
So the pressure
inside here is higher

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:03.820
than the pressure outside.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:05.910
But of course, from
what you know already

00:04:05.910 --> 00:04:09.280
about liquid mixtures, this
should in fact make sense.

00:04:09.280 --> 00:04:12.690
Because what's happening
is that if these things are

00:04:12.690 --> 00:04:15.670
at the same pressure, you know
that the chemical potential

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:18.250
of A is going to be
lower in the mixture.

00:04:18.250 --> 00:04:22.050
It's always lower in the
mixture than it is in pure A.

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:25.620
So there's nothing to
stop A from rushing in.

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:27.170
So A does rush in.

00:04:27.170 --> 00:04:31.830
If the liquid level goes up, it
raises the pressure down here.

00:04:31.830 --> 00:04:36.470
But as the pressure rises,
now the chemical potential

00:04:36.470 --> 00:04:38.520
changes and goes up.

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:41.290
So eventually, equilibrium
is reestablished.

00:04:41.290 --> 00:04:43.040
Because these aren't
at the same pressure.

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:45.890
The additional pressure means
the chemical potential of A

00:04:45.890 --> 00:04:46.680
goes up.

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:49.570
Of course, it goes down by
virtue of being in the mixture.

00:04:49.570 --> 00:04:52.426
And those two things will
eventually reach an equilibrium

00:04:52.426 --> 00:04:53.800
where the chemical
potential of A

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:57.550
is the same everywhere,
as it has to be.

00:04:57.550 --> 00:04:59.930
So what we'll
calculate now is, OK,

00:04:59.930 --> 00:05:02.210
how much does the
pressure go up.

00:05:02.210 --> 00:05:04.140
When that happens.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:05.467
So let's take a look.

00:05:05.467 --> 00:05:07.550
And so of course, there
are all kinds of examples.

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:09.340
In a typical one,
A would be water.

00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:11.310
And B would be one
or more sugars.

00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:14.790
All sorts of other
potential constituents also.

00:05:14.790 --> 00:05:18.820
OK, so let's just
consider the pressure

00:05:18.820 --> 00:05:21.090
at two places that
are the same level.

00:05:21.090 --> 00:05:22.500
The same height.

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:25.640
We'll label this
one point alpha.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:41.710
Let's put some color in here.

00:05:41.710 --> 00:05:46.690
We'll have points
alpha and beta.

00:05:46.690 --> 00:05:54.450
And we'll make this distance l.

00:05:54.450 --> 00:05:55.970
So now let's just
first calculate

00:05:55.970 --> 00:05:57.764
what the pressure
is at both points.

00:05:57.764 --> 00:05:59.430
It's going to be
higher here, because of

00:05:59.430 --> 00:06:01.340
this additional liquid on top.

00:06:01.340 --> 00:06:11.130
So, if we look at
point alpha, well,

00:06:11.130 --> 00:06:12.630
let's start at point
beta, actually.

00:06:12.630 --> 00:06:14.254
That's the simpler
one since it doesn't

00:06:14.254 --> 00:06:17.800
have the additional liquid.

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:22.470
And first of all, there's
just atmospheric pressure.

00:06:22.470 --> 00:06:26.140
So there's an external pressure.

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:28.960
Certainly, typically, it would
just be atmosphere pressure.

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:30.880
It's pushing down here.

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:36.560
It's also there.

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:44.090
So that has to factor in.

00:06:44.090 --> 00:06:48.060
So there's our
external pressure.

00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:53.410
And then there is the
product of this height

00:06:53.410 --> 00:06:58.370
times the density
of the solution.

00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:02.740
Times the gravitational
force constant.

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:05.070
And I'll work through
that momentarily

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:07.690
so you see that that
indeed is the pressure.

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:10.770
That's exerted by
the amount of liquid

00:07:10.770 --> 00:07:14.360
that's up above this level.

00:07:14.360 --> 00:07:22.040
But before I do that, let's put
the pressure at point alpha.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:23.690
So p alpha.

00:07:23.690 --> 00:07:29.840
And that's p external
plus l rho g.

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:35.910
But now, there's this additional
height on top of that.

00:07:35.910 --> 00:07:40.960
So there's also h rho g.

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:44.730
There's an extra pressure.

00:07:44.730 --> 00:07:55.510
We'll label this pi.

00:07:55.510 --> 00:08:05.080
So we can write p alpha is
equals to p beta plus h rho g.

00:08:05.080 --> 00:08:15.280
Which we'll say is
equal to p beta plus pi.

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:18.290
Now, just to make sure
we're all on the same page

00:08:18.290 --> 00:08:21.310
about these quantities
being the pressure that's

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:23.690
exerted by the liquid,
let's just look at that.

00:08:23.690 --> 00:08:38.800
So l times rho times g.

00:08:38.800 --> 00:08:45.280
It should be a pressure which
is a force per unit area.

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:56.200
And in particular, this is going
to be a weight per unit area.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:09:02.100
Remember the weight is the
force that a mass exerts.

00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:05.820
And it exerts it because of
the gravitational constant.

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:07.600
So what happens?

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:17.490
Well, this is just a length.

00:09:17.490 --> 00:09:22.600
Rho is a density, right?

00:09:22.600 --> 00:09:36.630
So it's mass per unit volume.

00:09:36.630 --> 00:09:47.690
And of course, g is just our
gravitational force constant.

00:09:47.690 --> 00:09:53.110
So it'll be in units of
meters per second squared.

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:55.100
So what's going to happen?

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:58.710
If we multiply l
times rho together,

00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:00.210
this is units of length.

00:10:00.210 --> 00:10:01.890
This is units of volume.

00:10:01.890 --> 00:10:06.005
What we're going to get
then is mass per unit area.

00:10:06.005 --> 00:10:07.380
And that's what
it is, of course.

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:11.160
It's distributing across
the area of that surface

00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:13.310
where point alpha is.

00:10:13.310 --> 00:10:20.350
So these two
together, l times rho,

00:10:20.350 --> 00:10:29.270
give us mass per unit area.

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:34.970
So it could be in
units of kilograms.

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:38.370
Per unit area, per
meters squared.

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:41.550
And now we're going to multiply
that by the gravitational force

00:10:41.550 --> 00:10:42.460
constant.

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:47.790
So now we're going
to have all together

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:55.240
kilograms per meter
second squared.

00:10:55.240 --> 00:11:11.370
In other words, it's
force per unit area.

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:13.090
And so that's what we have.

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:15.430
And now, of course, we have
the additional component.

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:22.020
Due to the height here.

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:24.740
Now, what do we know about
the chemical potential

00:11:24.740 --> 00:11:25.770
in both parts?

00:11:25.770 --> 00:11:27.430
The chemical potential
has to be equal

00:11:27.430 --> 00:11:31.590
outside and inside
the container.

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:45.880
So mu A at point
alpha is just mu A

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:54.070
of the liquid at pressure p
plus pi and temperature T.

00:11:54.070 --> 00:12:00.170
And that has to be equal
to mu A at point beta.

00:12:00.170 --> 00:12:03.400
But point beta is just
in the pure liquid.

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:08.155
So that's just mu A
star of the liquid

00:12:08.155 --> 00:12:15.350
at pressure p and
temperature T. So here's

00:12:15.350 --> 00:12:22.960
the chemical potential
at point beta.

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:24.470
Here it is at point alpha.

00:12:24.470 --> 00:12:26.570
Those two have to be
equal to each other.

00:12:26.570 --> 00:12:32.310
And now we're just going
to use Raoult's law.

00:12:32.310 --> 00:12:33.820
And what does that tell us?

00:12:33.820 --> 00:12:44.280
We have RT log of xA plus mu A
star of the liquid at pressure

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:49.460
p plus pi and T So there
is our chemical potential

00:12:49.460 --> 00:12:51.780
inside the container.

00:12:51.780 --> 00:13:01.110
And that's equal to mu A star of
the pure liquid at point beta.

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:09.150
And so we can just
rewrite this as RT log xA.

00:13:09.150 --> 00:13:16.080
Plus mu A star liquid
at pressure p plus pi

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:25.640
of T minus mu A star at
pressure p is equal to zero.

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:29.510
OK., now we need the
pressure dependence

00:13:29.510 --> 00:13:31.610
of the chemical potential.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:37.320
But we certainly have
an expression for that.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:47.440
So we know that dG
is S dT plus V dp.

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:49.450
The temperature is the
same on both sides.

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:53.880
But we need to worry about what
happens at different pressures.

00:13:53.880 --> 00:14:04.930
So at constant T, dG is V dp.

00:14:04.930 --> 00:14:07.390
So now if we look at the
chemical potential, which

00:14:07.390 --> 00:14:12.980
is just the Gibbs
free energy per mole,

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:28.050
then d mu A star is
VA star molar dp.

00:14:28.050 --> 00:14:30.620
In other words, the difference
in the chemical potential

00:14:30.620 --> 00:14:33.190
is, this changes as a
function of pressure.

00:14:33.190 --> 00:14:36.900
Is going to be given by
the molar volume of a

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:39.630
under these conditions
in the pure liquid dp.

00:14:45.720 --> 00:14:47.810
It's just the potential,
the pressure dependence

00:14:47.810 --> 00:14:52.510
of G. It's not the kind of
topic I would have thought

00:14:52.510 --> 00:14:54.110
would drive away
a lot of people.

00:14:54.110 --> 00:14:56.560
But, you never know.

00:14:56.560 --> 00:14:59.264
OK.

00:14:59.264 --> 00:15:01.430
For the rest of you who are
willing to bear with me,

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:06.600
let's continue.

00:15:06.600 --> 00:15:08.620
So now let's just integrate.

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:14.200
We need to know the change in mu
A at a finite jump in pressure

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:17.060
from inside to
outside the container.

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:19.540
So we're just
going to integrate.

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:30.380
So if I want mu A
star at pressure p

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:39.180
plus pi minus mu A
star at pressure p,

00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:49.130
then I just have to integrate
from p to p plus pi VA bar star

00:15:49.130 --> 00:15:50.207
dp.

00:15:50.207 --> 00:15:52.290
And now I'm going to assume,
and this is certainly

00:15:52.290 --> 00:15:56.460
a safe assumption, that this
quantity this, molar volume,

00:15:56.460 --> 00:15:57.690
isn't going to change.

00:15:57.690 --> 00:16:00.250
In other words, the
molar volume of liquid A

00:16:00.250 --> 00:16:02.340
isn't going to
change significantly,

00:16:02.340 --> 00:16:05.360
going from the pressure out
here to the pressure in here.

00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:08.220
On the grand scale of things
it's a small pressure change.

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:10.930
We can assume that the
liquid is incompressible

00:16:10.930 --> 00:16:13.877
over that small pressure change.

00:16:13.877 --> 00:16:15.710
Which means that this
is constant, since all

00:16:15.710 --> 00:16:27.330
we have then is simply
VA bar star times pi.

00:16:27.330 --> 00:16:30.930
So then, substituting
back here, so now

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:32.890
we've calculated
this difference,

00:16:32.890 --> 00:16:35.340
it's a simple result.

00:16:35.340 --> 00:16:42.980
So then we simply have
that RT log xA plus VA bar

00:16:42.980 --> 00:16:50.810
star pi is equal to zero.

00:16:50.810 --> 00:16:55.020
Now, you saw last time,
and I'll work through this

00:16:55.020 --> 00:17:01.950
quickly again,
that the log of xA

00:17:01.950 --> 00:17:08.660
can be written approximately
as minus nB over nA

00:17:08.660 --> 00:17:11.530
if you remember, this
came from writing

00:17:11.530 --> 00:17:17.460
that this is equal to
the log of one minus xB.

00:17:17.460 --> 00:17:21.650
But we're assuming that B is
the minor constituent here.

00:17:21.650 --> 00:17:25.070
So xB is a small number.

00:17:25.070 --> 00:17:30.840
So that this is roughly
equal to minus xB.

00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:38.430
And that's just minus
nB over nA plus nB.

00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:40.760
And since nB is much
smaller than nA,

00:17:40.760 --> 00:17:48.400
this is approximately
equal to minus nB over nA.

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:51.540
So we're going to make
this substitution.

00:17:51.540 --> 00:17:55.300
Also, this quantity,
this molar volume

00:17:55.300 --> 00:18:04.200
of A over the pure liquid, since
the concentration of B is low,

00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:06.180
we can assume that
this is just the molar

00:18:06.180 --> 00:18:09.610
volume of A in general.

00:18:09.610 --> 00:18:16.410
So, in other words, we
can write VA bar star.

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:21.600
We can just write it as VA bar.

00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:23.550
That is, we're
not going to worry

00:18:23.550 --> 00:18:25.340
about changes in
the molar volume,

00:18:25.340 --> 00:18:29.190
either as a function of pressure
or a function of concentration

00:18:29.190 --> 00:18:32.350
at the low concentrations
that we're working.

00:18:32.350 --> 00:18:39.730
And then, note that
nA times VA per mole

00:18:39.730 --> 00:18:41.710
is just the total volume.

00:18:41.710 --> 00:18:43.450
Oops, not bar.

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:44.550
Not the molar quantity.

00:18:44.550 --> 00:18:46.260
This is the molar
quantity multiplied

00:18:46.260 --> 00:18:49.120
by the number of moles.

00:18:49.120 --> 00:18:54.360
So it just gives us VA, the
total volume, occupied by A.

00:18:54.360 --> 00:19:05.040
And using these two results,
then we have that RT times

00:19:05.040 --> 00:19:11.160
negative nB over nA,
that's this result.

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:21.970
Plus VA over nA times pi is
equal to zero. nA will cancel.

00:19:21.970 --> 00:19:27.420
And finally, since almost
all the volume is due to A,

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:30.220
again because B is
the minor constituent,

00:19:30.220 --> 00:19:39.060
we can approximate further that
VA is approximately equal to V.

00:19:39.060 --> 00:19:43.900
So finally getting rid of
the nA on the denominators,

00:19:43.900 --> 00:19:46.650
we're left with a
simple expression.

00:19:46.650 --> 00:19:58.500
pi times V is RT nB.

00:19:58.500 --> 00:20:00.670
So we have a very
simple expression

00:20:00.670 --> 00:20:04.190
which is called the
van't Hoff expression,

00:20:04.190 --> 00:20:08.690
and look at how it
resembles the ideal gas law.

00:20:08.690 --> 00:20:11.170
This is the pressure
times the volume equals

00:20:11.170 --> 00:20:13.460
the number of moles times RT.

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:17.090
Of course, really it's
a change in pressure.

00:20:17.090 --> 00:20:18.950
And this number of
moles is the number

00:20:18.950 --> 00:20:24.620
of moles of a guest
constituent in a solution.

00:20:24.620 --> 00:20:29.860
But it has the same form
that you're familiar with.

00:20:29.860 --> 00:20:33.840
We also, sometimes it's
convenient to substitute,

00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:40.200
since nB over V, that's
just the concentration.

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:50.190
That's the number of
moles over the volume.

00:20:50.190 --> 00:20:52.110
And in that case,
the expression is

00:20:52.110 --> 00:20:58.100
rewritten as pi is RT times c,
where it's understood that this

00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:06.510
is the concentration
of the solute.

00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:14.320
OK, any questions?

00:21:14.320 --> 00:21:17.400
Let's work through
a numerical problem.

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:21.650
These things can seem a little
bit, they can seem simple,

00:21:21.650 --> 00:21:24.650
but sometimes when
confronted with a problem,

00:21:24.650 --> 00:21:27.580
sometimes it may seem less
than obvious what to do.

00:21:27.580 --> 00:21:30.200
And also the results can
seem a little bit surprising.

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:33.190
So I just want to work through
a simple numerical example

00:21:33.190 --> 00:21:34.850
to see how these play out.

00:21:34.850 --> 00:21:51.670
So let's try, let's imagine we
have 10 grams of unknown solid.

00:21:51.670 --> 00:22:09.780
Dissolved in 1000
grams of water.

00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:22.550
The vapor pressure is
25.195 torr at 27 degrees C.

