00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:21.550
Taller than any of us, by far.

00:31:21.550 --> 00:31:25.270
Sorry, it's up to there.

00:31:25.270 --> 00:31:26.730
And that's actually
pretty typical.

00:31:26.730 --> 00:31:31.450
And what that means is, it
actually makes osmotic pressure

00:31:31.450 --> 00:31:35.240
a very, very sensitive
measurement method.

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:39.430
If you want to determine a
molecular weight, for example.

00:31:39.430 --> 00:31:41.220
Because it's so
high, that means,

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:43.720
and of course you can measure
that height pretty accurately.

00:31:43.720 --> 00:31:46.420
Certainly within
about a millimeter.

00:31:46.420 --> 00:31:50.106
And so even relatively
modest concentrations,

00:31:50.106 --> 00:31:52.480
it's still easy to see the
effect and measure the impact.

00:31:52.480 --> 00:31:58.860
And use that to calculate
the properties of the solute.

00:31:58.860 --> 00:32:02.990
OK, any questions?

00:32:02.990 --> 00:32:07.840
Alright.

00:32:07.840 --> 00:32:10.770
Now we're going to
start something new.

00:32:10.770 --> 00:32:17.550
So, so far what you've seen,
and I hope come to appreciate,

00:32:17.550 --> 00:32:20.370
is the whole structure
of thermodynamics

00:32:20.370 --> 00:32:25.560
is built on empirical
macroscopic observation

00:32:25.560 --> 00:32:27.750
and deduction.

00:32:27.750 --> 00:32:29.030
We observe things.

00:32:29.030 --> 00:32:33.380
We formulate these broad
thermodynamic laws.

00:32:33.380 --> 00:32:34.370
All macroscopic.

00:32:34.370 --> 00:32:37.790
It doesn't depend on any
microscopic model at all.

00:32:37.790 --> 00:32:39.600
And in fact much of
it was formulated

00:32:39.600 --> 00:32:42.930
before there was a good
microscopic model of matter.

00:32:42.930 --> 00:32:45.610
Before the atomic theory
of matter, and molecules,

00:32:45.610 --> 00:32:50.230
and so forth was
well worked out.

00:32:50.230 --> 00:32:56.570
And it's incredible how powerful
that whole formalism is, right?

00:32:56.570 --> 00:32:58.830
In some sense,
although it may seem

00:32:58.830 --> 00:33:03.460
like neglecting what
we now know to be

00:33:03.460 --> 00:33:07.190
an important part of nature,
actually part of its power

00:33:07.190 --> 00:33:09.090
is its empiricism.

00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:09.680
Right?

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:12.010
There are these
very small number

00:33:12.010 --> 00:33:16.579
of fundamental laws from
which everything else follows.

00:33:16.579 --> 00:33:18.120
And at this point,
of course, there's

00:33:18.120 --> 00:33:21.240
just enormous confidence in
that small number of laws.

00:33:21.240 --> 00:33:24.690
Because of their being
verified in so many context.

00:33:24.690 --> 00:33:29.180
But, at the same
time, we do know

00:33:29.180 --> 00:33:31.340
about the atomic
theory of matter.

00:33:31.340 --> 00:33:33.920
We know there are
atoms and molecules.

00:33:33.920 --> 00:33:37.650
So it ought to be possible,
at least in principle,

00:33:37.650 --> 00:33:42.350
to start from a purely
microscopic approach to nature.

00:33:42.350 --> 00:33:48.650
And just based on figuring out
the microscopic properties.

00:33:48.650 --> 00:33:50.970
And then saying, well,
OK, my macroscopic stuff

00:33:50.970 --> 00:33:55.240
is just a collection of
those microscopic entities.

00:33:55.240 --> 00:33:59.240
I should also be able to figure
out macroscopic thermodynamics.

00:33:59.240 --> 00:34:02.380
I should be able to start
from my microscopic picture

00:34:02.380 --> 00:34:06.890
and get to macroscopic
thermodynamic results.

00:34:06.890 --> 00:34:08.760
And in fact, that is possible.

00:34:08.760 --> 00:34:11.210
And the theoretical
formulation for it

00:34:11.210 --> 00:34:13.180
is what's called
statistical mechanics.

00:34:13.180 --> 00:34:15.710
Called that because,
of course, you

00:34:15.710 --> 00:34:18.650
won't be surprised
to learn that it's

00:34:18.650 --> 00:34:21.090
going to require a
statistical treatment.

00:34:21.090 --> 00:34:23.660
We're going to be dealing
with moles of material.

00:34:23.660 --> 00:34:26.030
But now we're going
to be trying to think

00:34:26.030 --> 00:34:28.920
about their
microscopic properties.

00:34:28.920 --> 00:34:33.500
And so we'll be dealing not with
n number of moles, but with 10

00:34:33.500 --> 00:34:37.650
to the 24th number of
molecules or atoms.

00:34:37.650 --> 00:34:40.180
And you know we won't
be able to keep track

00:34:40.180 --> 00:34:44.890
of every one of their
individual states, all the time.

00:34:44.890 --> 00:34:48.330
We may be able to do a terrific
calculation of the quantum

00:34:48.330 --> 00:34:50.660
mechanics or the
classical mechanics that

00:34:50.660 --> 00:34:54.070
describe the states
that they could be in.

00:34:54.070 --> 00:34:56.070
But there's no way in
practice that we're either

00:34:56.070 --> 00:34:59.070
going to experimentally
or theoretically keep

00:34:59.070 --> 00:35:01.580
track of all of that.

00:35:01.580 --> 00:35:03.280
So we're going
to, at some point,

00:35:03.280 --> 00:35:05.700
have to introduce statistics.

00:35:05.700 --> 00:35:08.750
To take what we know about
the microscopic properties

00:35:08.750 --> 00:35:11.920
and try to go from there
to the macroscopic results.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:14.100
The thermodynamics
that we've seen so far.

00:35:14.100 --> 00:35:34.050
And that's what statistical
mechanics is all about.

00:35:34.050 --> 00:35:42.560
So let's try to
introduce a little bit

00:35:42.560 --> 00:35:44.070
of statistical mechanics.

00:35:44.070 --> 00:35:46.400
Where we're going
to go from what

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:49.010
we know about
microscopic properties

00:35:49.010 --> 00:35:51.870
all the way to macroscopic
thermodynamics.

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:58.510
That's our objective.

00:35:58.510 --> 00:36:04.100
So let's start by just
trying to calculate

00:36:04.100 --> 00:36:06.080
energies of
individual molecules,

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:08.500
or individual particles.

00:36:08.500 --> 00:36:13.790
And what's the probability
that some molecule, one

00:36:13.790 --> 00:36:16.870
of the oxygen molecules
somewhere in this room,

00:36:16.870 --> 00:36:18.870
is in a certain energy state.

00:36:18.870 --> 00:36:20.380
Right?

00:36:20.380 --> 00:36:22.280
And what our strategy
is going to be,

00:36:22.280 --> 00:36:26.420
is to determine what are the
probabilities that molecules

00:36:26.420 --> 00:36:29.880
are in certain states
with certain energies.

00:36:29.880 --> 00:36:33.820
And if we can determine that
for all the possible states,

00:36:33.820 --> 00:36:36.250
then we can average over those.

00:36:36.250 --> 00:36:40.450
So without keeping track of
every individual molecule,

00:36:40.450 --> 00:36:42.879
we could then calculate,
an average energy,

00:36:42.879 --> 00:36:44.920
which is what you would
measure thermodynamically

00:36:44.920 --> 00:36:47.169
when you look at the whole
collection and measure what

00:36:47.169 --> 00:36:48.790
we call u, right?

00:36:48.790 --> 00:36:50.190
Of course, we're
really averaging

00:36:50.190 --> 00:36:53.750
over disparate energies
of lots of different atoms

00:36:53.750 --> 00:36:54.820
or molecules.

00:36:54.820 --> 00:36:58.210
They don't all have the
same molecular energy.

00:36:58.210 --> 00:37:01.930
And we don't try to measure
their individual energies.

00:37:01.930 --> 00:37:03.690
So that's what we'd
like to calculate.

00:37:03.690 --> 00:37:06.620
And so we'd like
to be able to know

00:37:06.620 --> 00:37:10.790
what are all these probabilities
of different energy states.

00:37:10.790 --> 00:37:13.440
And then from
that, statistically

00:37:13.440 --> 00:37:17.210
averaging, what are the
macroscopic average energies.

00:37:17.210 --> 00:37:19.710
And other macroscopic
quantities.

00:37:19.710 --> 00:37:22.550
So, let's start there.

00:37:22.550 --> 00:37:40.030
Probability that a
molecule, must be specific

00:37:40.030 --> 00:37:50.910
as possible is in
state i with energy Ei.

00:37:50.910 --> 00:37:52.825
And right now we're
not even going

00:37:52.825 --> 00:37:55.580
to specify the
nature of the state.

00:37:55.580 --> 00:37:59.190
We could be worrying about
translational energy.

00:37:59.190 --> 00:38:02.800
What state it is, how fast
it's whizzing around the room.

00:38:02.800 --> 00:38:05.680
We could worry about its
vibrational or rotational

00:38:05.680 --> 00:38:07.500
energy, or electronic state.

00:38:07.500 --> 00:38:09.870
For now, let's not
even specify it.

00:38:09.870 --> 00:38:11.830
Let's just say the
only thing we're really

00:38:11.830 --> 00:38:14.360
specifying about
the state is it has

00:38:14.360 --> 00:38:19.200
some energy that
we presumably know.

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:27.460
Now, what we'd like is
to know a functional

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:29.930
form for the probability.

00:38:29.930 --> 00:38:32.530
And we don't know one a priori.

00:38:32.530 --> 00:38:38.570
But let's just think
about two molecules.

00:38:38.570 --> 00:38:40.990
And the probability
that one of them

00:38:40.990 --> 00:38:45.450
has energy i, and another
one has energy Ej.

00:38:45.450 --> 00:38:48.370
It also, let me say, would be
sufficient to think about even

00:38:48.370 --> 00:38:50.040
one molecule and
say, we'll let's

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:52.417
think about independent
parts of its energy.

00:38:52.417 --> 00:38:54.500
Let's say, translational
energy in this direction.

00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:56.680
And in an orthogonal direction.

00:38:56.680 --> 00:39:02.190
What matters is, we're thinking
about two independent energies.

00:39:02.190 --> 00:39:05.160
Could be separate molecules
that aren't interacting.

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:08.930
Or independent degrees of
freedom on the same molecule.

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:12.500
But let's just consider it.

00:39:12.500 --> 00:39:25.360
So a molecule is in state
i, and that another molecule

00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:35.870
is in state j, with energy Ej.

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:39.110
So what we're going to calculate
is the joint probability

00:39:39.110 --> 00:39:42.830
that the two molecules
are in those states.

00:39:42.830 --> 00:39:46.040
So we want a probability.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:52.090
This one, we'll call Pi(Ei).

00:39:52.090 --> 00:39:58.100
This would be Pj of Ej.

00:39:58.100 --> 00:40:00.370
And this probability together
will be Pij(Ei + Ej).

00:40:05.680 --> 00:40:09.400
I could just write Ei comma
Ej, but the energy's add.

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:14.120
And that's crucial.

00:40:14.120 --> 00:40:17.600
Now, since the molecules
are completely independent,

00:40:17.600 --> 00:40:29.850
this should just be the product
of the separate probabilities.

00:40:29.850 --> 00:40:32.420
Two completely
independent events,

00:40:32.420 --> 00:40:37.210
or things whose probability
we want to determine together.

00:40:37.210 --> 00:40:41.320
So, that suggests a really
simple functional form.

00:40:41.320 --> 00:40:48.070
Because what we're saying here
is we want a function of a plus

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:54.000
b, which is equal to the same
sort of function of a times

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:55.910
the same sort of function of b.

00:40:55.910 --> 00:40:59.100
In other words, when we
multiply these functions,

00:40:59.100 --> 00:41:05.460
we get a function of the
sum of those arguments.

00:41:05.460 --> 00:41:11.800
What functional form does that?

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:12.770
Exponential.

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:17.150
Sure.

00:41:17.150 --> 00:41:21.000
So in other words,
e to the a plus

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:27.240
b power equals e to
the a times e to the b.

00:41:27.240 --> 00:41:35.000
So it suggests that there's
an exponential probability.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:37.740
Suggests it.

00:41:37.740 --> 00:41:49.160
Now, there's also
some physical insight

00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:51.940
that we can apply
to the problem.

00:41:51.940 --> 00:41:56.040
First of all, we
expect that states

00:41:56.040 --> 00:41:57.550
with higher energy
in general are

00:41:57.550 --> 00:42:02.700
going to be less probable
than states with lower energy.

00:42:02.700 --> 00:42:06.205
If it's cold, not much
thermal energy around,

00:42:06.205 --> 00:42:07.580
and you say, how
much energy does

00:42:07.580 --> 00:42:11.570
a particle in an equilibrium
collection of particles have,

00:42:11.570 --> 00:42:15.370
at thermal equilibrium, if
there's not much thermal energy

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:17.830
around, you don't expect
it to be very likely

00:42:17.830 --> 00:42:19.760
that a particle has a
huge amount of energy.

00:42:19.760 --> 00:42:21.390
That one individual
particle has it.

00:42:21.390 --> 00:42:22.970
Could happen, right?

00:42:22.970 --> 00:42:24.660
From some random
collisions that just

00:42:24.660 --> 00:42:28.780
happened to bulk up the
energy of that one particle.

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:31.330
But on a balance it's not
going to be very probable.

00:42:31.330 --> 00:42:34.200
Lower energies will
be more probable.

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:37.030
And the other thing is, even
in thinking about something

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:39.880
like that, temperature comes in.

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:40.950
Immediately.

00:42:40.950 --> 00:42:42.262
Right?

00:42:42.262 --> 00:42:43.720
If you raise the
temperature a lot,

00:42:43.720 --> 00:42:46.800
surely we have to expect
many more molecules will

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:48.410
start to become energized.

00:42:48.410 --> 00:42:50.890
Will have more energy.

00:42:50.890 --> 00:42:55.230
So, lower probability
for higher energy.

00:42:55.230 --> 00:42:56.730
But the probability
of higher energy

00:42:56.730 --> 00:42:59.780
should go up if the
temperature goes up.

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:03.930
In other words, the ratio
of energy to temperature

00:43:03.930 --> 00:43:06.330
should be involved here.

00:43:06.330 --> 00:43:20.910
So, P of Ei should go
down as Ei goes up.

00:43:20.910 --> 00:43:30.930
And should depend
on Ei over T. Right?

00:43:30.930 --> 00:43:35.800
So, we can start with
this functional form.

00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:40.070
And by the way, there's
no reason we can't have,

00:43:40.070 --> 00:43:42.740
in general we would have
some constants here, right?

00:43:42.740 --> 00:43:45.870
We haven't changed
anything to do that.

00:43:45.870 --> 00:43:48.900
And now let's just
use the little bit

00:43:48.900 --> 00:43:53.220
of physical intuition that
we're thinking about here,

00:43:53.220 --> 00:43:55.640
to refine this
just a little bit.

00:43:55.640 --> 00:44:00.570
Let's write, we
expect that Pi of Ei

00:44:00.570 --> 00:44:10.210
is some exponential to
the minus C Ei over T,

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:13.130
where C is some constant
greater than zero.

00:44:13.130 --> 00:44:17.620
So this will have the property,
then, that as energy goes up,

00:44:17.620 --> 00:44:18.940
the probability goes down.

00:44:18.940 --> 00:44:20.560
But it's scaled by temperature.

00:44:20.560 --> 00:44:24.570
If I raise the temperature, that
makes the higher energy states

00:44:24.570 --> 00:44:30.500
get more and more likely.

00:44:30.500 --> 00:44:39.270
Well, this is our
functional form

00:44:39.270 --> 00:44:43.320
for probability of a
molecule being in a state

00:44:43.320 --> 00:44:44.980
with energy Ei.

00:44:44.980 --> 00:44:47.170
And the only difference
between this and what's

00:44:47.170 --> 00:44:51.930
written conventionally is the
way the constant is labeled.

00:44:51.930 --> 00:44:58.070
So really what we
have is Pi of Ei

00:44:58.070 --> 00:45:06.640
is proportional to e to the
minus Ei over kB T, or just k

00:45:06.640 --> 00:45:17.050
T, where kB is called
the Boltzmann constant.

00:45:17.050 --> 00:45:21.680
And it's just equal to R
over Avogadro's number.

00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:30.700
It's the gas constant per
molecule, rather than per mole.

00:45:30.700 --> 00:45:37.080
One way to try to rationalize
this is, you've probably seen,

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:40.580
you've all seen Arrhenius
kinetics, right?

00:45:40.580 --> 00:45:44.540
Arrhenius rate laws?

00:45:44.540 --> 00:45:53.140
If you remember what
that looks like,

00:45:53.140 --> 00:45:56.090
you get this rate constant.

00:45:56.090 --> 00:46:00.663
Arrhenius rate constant
is some constant A times e

00:46:00.663 --> 00:46:05.460
to the minus Ea over RT.

00:46:05.460 --> 00:46:07.510
Remember that?

00:46:07.510 --> 00:46:10.720
You've all seen that before?

00:46:10.720 --> 00:46:14.720
And so what's
happening here, Ea is

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:18.300
what is an activation energy.

00:46:18.300 --> 00:46:20.390
Remember, the idea
is that you've

00:46:20.390 --> 00:46:24.180
got reactants and
products, and there's

00:46:24.180 --> 00:46:26.140
some barrier you've
got to get over.

00:46:26.140 --> 00:46:29.480
The activation energy,
before you can have reaction.

00:46:29.480 --> 00:46:33.640
So the rate depends on
surmounting that activation

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:36.390
barrier.

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:39.960
This is really coming
from the same idea

00:46:39.960 --> 00:46:44.340
as this, which is the
probability of one

00:46:44.340 --> 00:46:47.920
of the molecules having
this much energy.

00:46:47.920 --> 00:46:51.230
Depends on e to the
minus energy over RT.

00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:53.320
This is per mole,
so this is per mole.

00:46:53.320 --> 00:46:55.980
The exact same relation.

00:46:55.980 --> 00:46:59.100
So the idea in the
context of kinetics

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:04.540
is that the rate depends on how
many molecules can get up here.

00:47:04.540 --> 00:47:07.690
And what the probability is
of their getting enough energy

00:47:07.690 --> 00:47:10.040
to go over the barrier.

00:47:10.040 --> 00:47:11.700
And that energy,
that probability,

00:47:11.700 --> 00:47:13.520
is given by this expression.

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:16.320
So in this form you've seen
this kind of dependence

00:47:16.320 --> 00:47:29.080
before in a very explicit way.

00:47:29.080 --> 00:47:36.740
Let me just take it one small
but important step farther.

00:47:36.740 --> 00:47:42.790
Which is that
proportionality constant.

00:47:42.790 --> 00:47:45.450
Couldn't we do better?

00:47:45.450 --> 00:47:49.560
Couldn't we say, couldn't we
figure out what exactly it is,

00:47:49.560 --> 00:47:52.520
not just what it's
proportional to?

00:47:52.520 --> 00:47:53.260
Well, let's try.

00:47:53.260 --> 00:47:58.850
So as we've written
it, we've got Pi of Ei

00:47:58.850 --> 00:48:03.660
is proportional to e to
the minus Ei over kT.

00:48:03.660 --> 00:48:08.150
We could write that as equals
A e to the minus Ei over kT.

00:48:08.150 --> 00:48:12.050
This is just some
proportionality constant.

00:48:12.050 --> 00:48:14.710
But we can determine
what that constant is,

00:48:14.710 --> 00:48:22.480
because we know that if we sum
over all the possible states,

00:48:22.480 --> 00:48:25.550
the molecule has to be
in some state, right?

00:48:25.550 --> 00:48:30.930
So that sum of all those
probabilities has to equal one.

00:48:30.930 --> 00:48:37.560
So sum over i of Pi of
Ei, is equal to one.

00:48:37.560 --> 00:48:44.270
Because the molecule must
be in one of the states.

00:48:44.270 --> 00:48:49.030
OK, now this is our expression
for all those p i's.

00:48:49.030 --> 00:48:52.790
So let's just write that way.
a is just a constant times

00:48:52.790 --> 00:49:03.130
the sum over all the i's of
e to the minus Ei over kT.

00:49:03.130 --> 00:49:09.480
And so there it is. a is equal
to one over the sum over i, e

00:49:09.480 --> 00:49:17.070
to the minus Ei over kT.

00:49:17.070 --> 00:49:25.160
So now we can
rewrite Pi of Ei is

00:49:25.160 --> 00:49:32.780
equal to e to the minus Ei
over kT over, the sum over i, e

00:49:32.780 --> 00:49:41.600
to the minus Ei over kT.

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:47.190
Now, just so you're not
confused, this i matters.

00:49:47.190 --> 00:49:48.772
That's the i we're
talking about.

00:49:48.772 --> 00:49:51.230
What's the probability of it
being in some particular state

00:49:51.230 --> 00:49:53.540
i with energy e i.

00:49:53.540 --> 00:49:55.390
This i is just a dummy variable.

00:49:55.390 --> 00:49:57.480
So just to be explicit,
we could write this just

00:49:57.480 --> 00:50:01.220
as well as e to the
minus Ei over kT

00:50:01.220 --> 00:50:09.760
times the sum over j, e
to the minus Ej over kT.

00:50:09.760 --> 00:50:11.890
It could be confusing, but
this is usually the way

00:50:11.890 --> 00:50:13.330
that it's written.

00:50:13.330 --> 00:50:15.760
Even though this
dummy variable here

00:50:15.760 --> 00:50:17.710
has nothing to do with
the particular choice

00:50:17.710 --> 00:50:23.550
that's made here.

00:50:23.550 --> 00:50:24.780
So now we know.

00:50:24.780 --> 00:50:29.370
And we can calculate what the
probability is for a molecule

00:50:29.370 --> 00:50:31.030
to be in any
particular state if we

00:50:31.030 --> 00:50:32.765
know the energy of that state.

00:50:32.765 --> 00:50:34.890
Now, notice we need to know
all the energies of all

00:50:34.890 --> 00:50:36.160
the other states, too.

00:50:36.160 --> 00:50:40.590
Because this thing,
in other words,

00:50:40.590 --> 00:50:45.440
this a, right, depends on
summing over all of those.

00:50:45.440 --> 00:50:48.020
But if we know those,
then we can do it.

00:50:48.020 --> 00:50:49.390
We can do the whole calculation.

00:50:49.390 --> 00:50:52.610
And for a good number of
cases, we realistically

00:50:52.610 --> 00:50:55.600
do know it all.

00:50:55.600 --> 00:51:00.120
So from the proportionality
relationship alone,

00:51:00.120 --> 00:51:03.610
of course, we can tell
the ratio of chances

00:51:03.610 --> 00:51:06.760
that you're in one
state or another.

00:51:06.760 --> 00:51:10.430
Even without this a
constant, we already

00:51:10.430 --> 00:51:13.640
could've said well, if
what's the ratio of,

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:18.890
the probability of being in
state i with energy Ei to state

00:51:18.890 --> 00:51:21.460
j with energy Ej.

00:51:21.460 --> 00:51:26.180
Well, it's just e to the
minus Ei over kT over e

00:51:26.180 --> 00:51:29.730
to the minus Ej over kT.

00:51:29.730 --> 00:51:37.110
It's e to the minus
Ei minus Ej over kT.

00:51:37.110 --> 00:51:39.440
But apart from just being
able to get the ratio,

00:51:39.440 --> 00:51:42.020
we can get the absolute number.

00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:44.225
What's the absolute
probability that a molecule

00:51:44.225 --> 00:51:50.260
is in any particular
state of a given energy.

00:51:50.260 --> 00:51:53.290
Next time what
you'll see is what

00:51:53.290 --> 00:51:56.390
can be calculated based on
the results that you've seen,

00:51:56.390 --> 00:52:00.570
just the results
you've seen so far.

00:52:00.570 --> 00:52:04.630
From these quantities
alone, it turns out

00:52:04.630 --> 00:52:07.930
you'll be able to calculate
every single macroscopic

00:52:07.930 --> 00:52:12.560
thermodynamic quantity.

00:52:12.560 --> 00:52:14.569
So you'll see some
of that next time.

